, developed by Damien Keown, whether there is such a thing as a Buddhist ethics at all. This has quite a lot to do with Zhang\u2019s discussion in the paper. Then I\u2019ll focus on Zhang\u2019s treatment of human rights and human freedom according to Buddhism, respectively.", "correspondence": {"affiliation": {"country": "Thailand", "@country": "tha", "city": "Bangkok", "organization": [{"$": "Department of Philosophy"}, {"$": "Faculty of Arts"}, {"$": "Chulalongkorn University"}], "ce:source-text": "Department of Philosophy, Faculty of Arts, Chulalongkorn University, Bangkok, Thailand"}, "person": {"ce:given-name": "Soraj", "ce:initials": "S.", "ce:surname": "Hongladarom", "ce:indexed-name": "Hongladarom S."}}, "citation-info": {"citation-type": {"@code": "ch"}, "citation-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}, "abstract-language": {"@language": "English", "@xml:lang": "eng"}}, "source": {"sourcetitle-abbrev": "Adv. Glob. Bioeth.", "website": {"ce:e-address": {"$": "springer.com/series/10420", "@type": "email"}}, "@country": "nld", "translated-sourcetitle": {"@xml:lang": "eng"}, "issn": [{"$": "22126538", "@type": "electronic"}, {"$": "2212652X", "@type": "print"}], "volisspag": {"voliss": {"@volume": "6"}, "pagerange": {"@first": "91", "@last": "96"}}, "@type": "k", "publicationyear": {"@first": "2017"}, "publisher": {"publishername": "Springer Science and Business Media B.V."}, "sourcetitle": "Advancing Global Bioethics", "@srcid": "21101039404", "publicationdate": {"year": "2017", "date-text": {"@xfab-added": "true", "$": "2017"}}}, "enhancement": {"classificationgroup": {"classifications": [{"@type": "ASJC", "classification": [{"$": "2739"}, {"$": "2910"}, {"$": "3306"}, {"$": "2719"}]}, {"@type": "SUBJABBR", "classification": [{"$": "MEDI"}, {"$": "NURS"}, {"$": "SOCI"}]}]}}}, "item-info": {"copyright": {"$": "Copyright 2021 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.", "@type": "Elsevier"}, "dbcollection": [{"$": "REAXYSCAR"}, {"$": "SCOPUS"}, {"$":